awd_titl_txt: Developing Design Criteria for Required Tension Development and Tension Splice Length for Reinforcing Bars Embedded in  High-Strength Concrete
awd_abstract_narration: 9402311  Azizinamini  Concern for safety and lack of information has resulted in the ACI  318-89 building code imposing a 10,000 psi limitation on concrete  compressive strength, that can be utilized  in the design process  when calculating tension development length of reinforcing bars.   This limitation is a result of the fact that the current code  requirements are based on test data form specimens with compressive  strengths in the range of 3,000 to 6,000 psi; however, concrete  with compressive strength exceeding 14,000 psi is being used in  construction.      The overall objective of the research is to develop a unified  theoretical model that would explain the behavior of deformed bars  embedded in concrete of any compressive strength.  Of particular  interest is the case of concrete with compressive strength  exceeding 14,000 psi.  Further, it is intended that the research  findings be provided in the code language format, adoptable by  code-writing organizations.
